The Higgs boson analyzes
The announcement of the likely discovery of the Higgs boson has caused some excitement last summer, and this for good reason.
In fact, it is believed that this Boson is involved in nothing less than the mechanism responsible for the mass of all objects in the universe.
And finally it is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model - our best or "at least false" explanation of nature and the behavior of matter - but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for the physicists it is not completely certain that it is really the Higgs.
We know without the shadow of a doubt that we have a real new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, this seems to be confirmed by new data presented this week at a large physics congress in Kyoto, but there is still no data to be absolutely sure about it.
Nevertheless, let us assume that this is actually the Higgs, as there seems to be only a small risk of being deceived, and let us look at what it is all about.
There is in this world an inevitable intransigable law that causes two objects to not be present at the same place at the same time.
It is not possible to violate this rule - and do not try it too strong as you will hurt.
For even if particle physics is a really strange world, it turns out that such a law applies to them too: the Pauli exclusion principle, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time when they are in the same "quantum state", with this "state" consisting in the bulk of some of their properties.
From that point on, the physicists divide the particles into two categories.
In one corner are the good citizens, who are called Fermione, who obey the Pauli principle.
And in the other, the bosons, an evil band of anarchists, who are not holy - certainly not this principle, which means that they can actually be located in the same place at the same time.
According to the website The Particle Adventure, these bosons are divided into two groups by the Berkeley Labors (which, by the way, is absolutely amazing): the mesons that we will not treat here and the "power particles" by which the great forces of nature are spread and with which the Higgs boson would somehow be related.
It must be stressed here, however, that these bosons are not all such exotic creatures as one might think.
If you are able to read this chronicle, then only thanks to a boson of extraordinary banality: the photon or the "light particle" which is the "bote" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, if a particle accelerates with an electric charge or changes the direction, the electromagnetic field is precisely "distorted" in this place, like a gravel stone that was thrown into a pond.
This "disturbation" creates an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon and thus one of the bosons "carriers of force".
Stable Field
The same applies to the Higgs boson, with the difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be "distorted" so that this boson shows itself.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; the pathogen has to achieve very high energies, a little comparable to a frozen pond whose surface could only be broken by a very large rock.
Therefore, a huge particle accelerator such as the CERN is required - the Large Hadron Collider is a ring with a size of 27 km! - to achieve such energies.
Analogy with the electromagnetic field is again helpful in explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
In fact, it is not all particles and not all materials that interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do this, but others do not - for example, a sheet of paper would never keep on the refrigerator itself.
And likewise, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those who do have a mass, while the others (as the photon) have no mass.
For what can all these research "be good," Mrs Plamondon asks?
For science, they serve to review the standard model (SM), and they also allow physicists to examine exactly all deviations between the observations and the forecasts of the SM.
By the way, there are numerous physicists who hope that such deviations will be found, because the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" and stop some holes of the model.
One must say that the latter still has great defects, as there is no explanation for gravity (ups!) and the dark matter that forms about 80% of the matter of the universe (renews ups!).
However, such deviations have not been found at CERN until now.
Impact
The impact of these research on the general population is more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there is no such thing.
By the way: in the early 1960s, the pioneers of the laser in the Bell Labs did not suspect that their works would trigger such a revolution.
They saw scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs in which the laser was invented in the 1960s, and who himself developed the first continuous strip laser (the first were pulsated) in 1962 - has already said that the laser was considered to be a "labor toys" at the beginning.
Imagine...
In addition, applications can also emerge from all the instruments surrounding research.
For example, Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in optics.
Although it was not the original purpose, today this sensor serves as an "eye" for all digital cameras worldwide and in 2009 it introduced the Nobel Prize for Physics.
Of course, this does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily change our lives, but it means that you can never really know...
Palliative care - the best way to die...  in Le Devoir
