The prostate cancer, which devoured him, had left him a period of two years.
"They gave me five years to live, I did seven years," he said, half-heartedly, lying in his bed in his home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois in a hurry where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, you can't be prepared for it," he says.
The disease makes her work: an immeasurable weakness prevents him from going to the toilet alone and even eating himself.
Sitting at the table in front of a delicious lunch, he agrees to let himself be helped with food.
Mutige even manages to smile and talk to the strangers who are busy around him, bring him his medications, and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
"My greatest wish is to heal my diarrhoea, as this is humiliating," he says.
A few hours later, the team found a cure for this evil.
"Over the course of our life, we learn that a man is stinging in the standing," says Pierre Brodeur, psychologist at Victor-Gadbois's home.
Returning back to childhood is unacceptable humiliation for some.
"This depends on the person's ability", he says, taking a step backwards.
In the opinion of several people who work in the palliative care, major events take place in the midst of these retreats.
The patients who are assigned to the home for palliative care Victor-Gadbois are all suffering from cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
At this stage they are no longer overcrowded by doctors and nurses who care for them with so-called "healing" care.
For Ms. A., 89 years, the worst fear is to die "consciously and by suffocation".
But through the illness, I really met my children.
"I have good children," she adds.
"I no longer have wishes in life," she says, before she accepts that she is set up a mask that helps her breathe.
She still expects a last visit to her son who comes from Italy in the next few days.
At the Victor-Gadbois home you can offer with a group of volunteers body care and help with food intake.
Palliative care is then used if there are no other possibilities.
To make dying more pleasant.
In Quebec there is a bed for palliative care on 11,700 inhabitants.
This is very little if you consider that one day we will all die.
Here life is continued under the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors of the home.
Both on the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
Depending on your wishes, you grant the dying person a mouth care with Brandy or Pepsi.
Diabetes patients no longer need to control their blood sugar levels.
And death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served Mr. X a beer that died during the night.
This morning his son will drink the beer at the feet of the deceased.
"We help relatives and patients alike," reports Natalie Savard.
Victor-Gadbois's home is not a day like the other.
In addition to an old 93-year-old man who enjoys the last family meeting in the yard and is well supported by his pillows, while one moves to his honor, a 36-year-old man who is surrounded by his parents, his wife and his two little children dies tragically after trying everything to survive.
"For six months three to five beds have always been occupied with cancer patients at the age of less than 45 years," Dr. Christiane Martel tells us alarmedly.
53% of patients admitted to Victor-Gadbois are from their home, 47% are from the hospital.
Access to palliative care
It is said that 77% of the Canadians do not have access to palliative care, i.e. care to relieve the suffering of patients when the latter reach the final stage of their lives, both at home, at the hospital or in a nursing home.
And several organizations such as the home Victor-Gadbois and the company for domestic palliative care in the Montreal area specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
This very great inadequacy in the health care of Quebec ensures that several doctors specialised in palliative care face with concern the adoption of a law on the regulation of death aid and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been in circulation, signed by prominent figures of palliative care such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, in order to express their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, the Quebec health system is not capable enough to ensure that all the right to high-quality palliative care is granted before accepting to go to death aid.
Recently, she says, I saw a patient who was in the emergency for 14 days with great pain, without taking measures to relieve them.
I fear that the patients only want to die because they do not receive adequate health care.
And at the same time, several oncologists treat their patients in spite of the worst prognosis to the last day.
The survival chances of Hélène Richard were minimal already when she stopped a difficult chemotherapy therapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was going to stop the treatment, she answered me that she was sorry that I was up the fight, she told me.
However, she had told me that I was at the end!
No omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who have asked to die thank the nurse for not accepting this wish after their pain has been eased by a team of palliative care.
However, it must be stated clearly that palliative care is not omnipotent in the pain treatment.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of the Palliative Care of the Company of the Home Palliative Care of the Grand Room Montreal, 8% of patients do not address pain treatment.
At the end of life, therefore, doctors often resort to the terminal sedation, which is due to either sporadic or permanent sedation of the patient until the time of his death.
We can no longer do as if we do not perceive this side of suffering.
Patients without pain relief will increasingly have the opportunity to access this terminal sedation.
Patients whose pains are not eased say the same sentence: "I want to die."
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want you to sleep me" but "I want my pain to be eased."
