Nevertheless, in an October report on virtual currencies, the European Central Bank (ECB) has shown interest in this.
She describes Bitcoin as "the virtual currency with the greatest success", "in competition with the dollar or euro" and "like the traditional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies such as the "Credits", which are used to advance in a video game that you can win or buy through games (and sometimes exchange them).
The social network Facebook has also developed such a system.
However, trading is controlled and processed each time by a central authority.
With Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously depositors of the billing book, auditors, money issuers as well as buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two e-mail addresses in the form of an e-mail.
With the difference that the user can choose a different address for each payment, which ensures anonymity.
A number of data related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double encryption system.
In this way, the network can verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Using the content of the file it is also possible to ensure that the traded bitcoins are present in the billbook of public accounts distributed throughout the network.
The decisive step is to insert this new transaction into this book.
This is done through a mathematical task launched on the computers, whereby the winner, who is a kind of provisional central banker who has privilege, adds this additional line.
It is a splitting of the file, i.e. the conversion of a large file into a shorter and unique electronic fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number to it before the whole thing is "caught".
The aim is to find the number that gives a special fingerprint (many zeros at the beginning).
If this number is found, the other nodes can effortlessly check if it is the right one.
The transaction is therefore permanently linked to the chain of all other transactions, and any modification would change the fingerprint.
If a user wants to pay with the same money for cheating twice very fast (less than 10 minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network and the other will remain without connection, as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the task receives 50 bitcoins.
To prevent inflation, this reward is regularly halved, probably before the end of 2012.
The bitcoins in circulation are therefore limited to 21 million, but can be shared up to a hundred millionth, leaving a certain amount of room...
In addition, the difficulty of the task is increased with each improvement of the computing power.
The life of the network has already had heights and depths.
The websites providing services for bitcoin were attacked and the bitcoin deposits stolen.
"The vulnerability used does not concern the actual protocol," says Pierre Noizat, who has just introduced Paymium, which is a real money payment company using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reports on the possibilities of money laundering through this anonymous service.
However, cash also shows these shortcomings.
Important actors like Wikipedia refuse donations of this kind.
They are accepted by others like the blog platform WordPress.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel analysed the billing book and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
In November a "Mega lock-sale" was launched.
"There were thirty thousand dollars exchanged," says Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of a book about this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
His system Paytunia corresponds to a credit card (with real money) or a contactless payment with a mobile phone, but uses Bitcoin to validate the transactions that are cheaper.
In addition, the holder manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system can be easily implemented by dealers, and the latter do not need to install new terminals or computer programs.
You just need to specify one address that can be "photographed and recognized" by a phone, Pierre Noizat says that he has thousands of users.
A general trend has to be seen in which hierarchical systems are considered in favour of more horizontally oriented systems.
"It will take some time for Bitcoin to go through, but 2013 could be a turning point," he predicts.
By the way, the ECB's report provides for the re-evaluation of the various risks that are considered to be high today in the event of a success of this currency.
