A Constitution with the Breaking Bar in Egypt
It is a new poker game by President Muhammad Mursi.
While Egypt remains more than ever divided in terms of the Constitutional Declaration, which temporarily grants it unlimited authority, it has decided to place everything on a map.
To the surprise of all, he announced on Wednesday that the constitutional assembly would adopt its final version on the next day.
Just a week ago, the head of state of this assembly had given two additional months for the completion of his work.
For almost two years now, Egypt has been based on a preliminary text that has been modified several times, which weakens institutional stability and leads to legal confusion.
This new initiative has only provided for an even greater division of the country.
For his opponents, the president persists in his "autocratic delirium" by continuing to "break his word" and "step the right with his feet".
On behalf of its supporters, it is assured that it is a way to end the institutional and political crisis as soon as possible and to speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held within 14 days.
A very short period of time which forces the brothers to refrain from their plans to explain to the Egyptians the text section for section.
For the president, it is also a way of reinventing its public and democratic legitimacy while protesting throughout the country.
After confirmations in an interview with the American weekly show Time, Muhammad Mursi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote well.
In particular, the Egyptian people with this back-up to an over-voting vote will have an ultimatum placed: "You either vote in favour of my draft or I maintain unlimited authority", the latter should supposedly end after adoption of the Constitution.
85 mostly Islamist members of this constitutional assembly adopted the text yesterday in a strange atmosphere.
The majority of the Liberals have failed to comply with the call.
Shortly before the Constitutional Declaration in mid-November, they turned away, as they believed they had not been able to apply their views.
Representatives of human rights organisations, religious minorities or civil society have acted equally.
In order to achieve decision-making capacity, 11 persons, alternate members, were added in all hurrys yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim brothers.
It is not surprising that most of the articles have been adopted unanimously.
The commentators, by the way, found it entertaining that the only difference in opinion of the day... was expressed in the time of prayer, because some members of the body felt that the pendial clock of the constituent assembly was not going exactly.
The text, which was adopted last night, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, which drew all attention to itself, is ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution and states that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
The Salafist parties, for which the establishment of Islamic law is an important requirement, had the hope of replacing "the principles" with "the rules", which would have made stricter application possible.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a proof of their good will and respect for the other members of the Egyptian society.
"Blessedness" is a response to the liberals who only regard this as a propaganda blow.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution takes place on other articles.
In doing so, they are particularly aware of Article 220, which gives the University of Al-Azhar an advisory function, particularly as regards the verification of conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, this is worrying because "the persons who are invited to an opinion have not been elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
One can see in this the first signs of a theocracy".
The fears of the liberals are also nourished by the fact that the next rector of this university is much less moderate than the current one.
"There is currently no real religious commitment to be recognized.
With this constitution we remain within the framework of the bourgeois state.
Most lawyers who have worked on this text are not Ulema, but academics who have been partially trained in the French system," explains Alexis Blouet, who writes a doctoral thesis on Egyptian constitutional transition.
However, he admits that "in relation to Article 220, there may be a plurality, as the terms used are derived from the religious vocabulary.
In particular, this refers to the "Fiqh" [Islamic case law, Rem. d. Red.].
And in the future, the question could be raised as to the extent to which civil courts are competent to decide."
In addition to his religious aspect, the text adopted yesterday is strongly criticised by the far-reaching powers he grants to the President of the Republic.
The Muslim brothers argue that compared to the former regime, these are significantly reduced.
Another point of dispute: the powers of the army.
In line with the military's wish, the examination of the defence budget is not submitted to Parliament but to a national defence council.
Similarly, there will be no ban on civil proceedings in military courts, as the human rights defence associations have requested.
The latter also communicate their fears about the text they consider to be a threat to freedom.
The deed of the blasphemy is maintained, and insults are now prohibited, which could have serious consequences for the right to freedom of expression, especially for the press.
Furthermore, no more article refers to the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayef by Human Rights Watch.
In her opinion, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture by Article 36.
This word was not included in the previous Constitution.
While the Egyptian President had to speak on television last night, demonstrations are scheduled for this afternoon.
The supporters of the Head of State will march on Saturday.
In Israel, Ukrainian tourists expect sacred places, the navel of the world and a sea of Sole
The Blessed Land unites in itself the glory of Bible truths, modern comfort and an unspoiled nature.
AIF mentions the five main reasons for visiting Israel.
Move before the Holy Places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It means that all those who bathe in this river receive God's blessing.
Galilee is the place where Jesus performed his miracles: the transformation of water into wine at a wedding feast, walking on the water, the silence of the sea storm and the fishing.
Here Jesus appeared to his disciples after the resurrection.
Most sanctuaries, however, are found in Jerusalem.
Here, believers go on the path of suffering or the crossroads of Jesus Christ (on Latin: Via Dolorosa).
The path begins at the Roman fortress of Antonia, Pretorium, where was the court, and leads through the streets of the old town to the tomb church on Mount Golgotha, where the crucifixion, the anointing stone and the grave of Jesus are located.
Here, according to Christian opinion, is the navel of the world that symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
The monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem stands in the place where a Christian legend says that the tree from which the cross was made for the crucifixion of Jesus grew.
In Jerusalem there is also the most holy place of the Jews - the wall of appeal, the remains of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 C.E.
Traditionally, people of various faiths leave Zettel with wishes that will then be fulfilled.
Take a trip to the altitude
The ruins of the fortress of Massada form the remains of the secret hiding from enemies that Herod the Great had built for his family in the year 25 A.D.
They are located on a rocky wall in the mountains at 450 meters above sea level.
Only climbers can reach the ruins by themselves.
Everyone else brings an airstrip to this historic summit.
In the north of the country at 1600 to 2040 meters altitude is the famous ski resort Hermon, where it attracts countless tourists in the winter months.
From the foot of the mountain you can reach with a shuttle bus.
The ski slopes have a total length of 45 kilometres.
According to an old legend, pagan gods lived on the mountaintop.
Visit unique museums
There are almost 300 museums in this country.
On just one trip, not all of them can be visited.
But at least the five most interesting of them should be paid a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum not far from the Knesset (Parliament).
There, old Qumran manuscripts or scrolls are stored from the Dead Sea found in Felshöhlen in the Judean Desert and about 500 thousand archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Museum of Art in Tel Aviv is also worth a visit.
There the collection of works by Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissaro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso is exhibited.
In Akko you can visit the museum in the Bad Al Basha, which houses several rooms of old Turkish baths with sculptures of the then visitors and bathing servants.
In Caesarea you should visit the unique private Ralli Museum, where you can admire sculptures of Dali and Rodin.
There are neither museum guides nor souvenir shops.
Admission is free and donations are rejected in principle.
The fifth museum, namely the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv, tells of one of the most devastating chapters of history.
The most moving department is the monument for the children built in memory of the 1.5 million children destroyed in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
There is total darkness when entering the room.
Star functioning.
And the names of the Jewish children and the lands in which they died are heard.
Ukraine is also mentioned there.
Do something for health
The three main recreational areas of Israel lie on the shores of the Mediterranean, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
At each of the three places there are swimming pools, water parks, dolphinaries and oceanariums.
Amazingly, in the Red Sea also in the winter months, as the water temperature does not fall below 21 °C and the air warms up to 23 °C.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and bathed throughout the year.
By the way, this unusual sea with a location of 417 meters below sea level is the deepest sea in the world.
Its turquoise blue water has a high salt content and thus even carries no swimmer easily on the surface.
The surrounding landscape is indescribably beautiful.
Visitors come here for treatments using salt water (natural salt solsole) and medicinal sludge, as well as for the treatment of skin inflammation, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, and for the calming of stressed nerves.
Touching the Secrets of Age
This is the secret of the old town of Tel Aviv, the town of Jaffa on the Mediterranean coast.
Through this city was the famous sea route that linked Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in ancient Greek and ancient Egyptian legends.
According to tradition, Noah built his ark right here, and Perseus saved here the beautiful Andromeda, with which he lived a long and happy life in this place.
Tourists like to wander through the narrow streets named after constellations.
Fortuna is to be the legend according to all the hold that touches the walls in the alley with its star sign.
In Jaffa you can find newly married couples from all over Israel and even other countries at photo dates.
In Caesarea, the city of King Herod, you can strip through the Roman theatre and conquer the fortress of the Crusades.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the most important city of Judea and residence of the Roman governors, including Pontius Pilate.
In the carefully restored theatre, evening concerts and operas are performed today.
Favourites for tourists
If you go to Israel, don't worry about your bad English skills: About 30% of Israelis speak Russian.
The money in the trip is not taken into euros, but in dollars that can easily be changed into shekels (current exchange rate: 1 dollar to 3.8 shekel).
In the city you usually get ahead by bus, but in Jerusalem there is also a highway and in Haifa the only underground line of the country with six stations that connect the underground with the Upper Town.
In fact, it's an underground cable car.
A trip within the city costs 6 shekels regardless of the transport, which includes switching for a trip of up to 1.5 hours.
According to Jewish tradition, the Sabbath is celebrated in Israel on Saturday.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturday markets and shops are closed, and public transport rests.
And on Sunday morning the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and restaurants, only cosheral food is served, excluding pig meat, sea products, fish without scales and food containing both milk and meat products.
Instead, you have the choice between different dishes with hammel and beef, soups and desserts (prepared with coconut milk), traditional Jewish humus paste, different sauces, dried balls of pure beans and peas (palas) as well as fruits and vegetables.
In the streets of Israeli cities there are no soothing dogs.
For this there are many well-nourished cats that roam comfortably and unlightened through the streets.
In the evening, they are even seen sleeping on the roofs of parking cars.
The cats like lively places and don't say no to treats.
A car rental costs between 37 dollars per day (Hyundai Getz) and 188 dollars (Audi A6, Volvo S80).
In addition, insurance costs $15 a day.
And bike rental costs 15 shekels a day.
Tickets for museums cost 30 shekels on average.
In figures
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most adventurers and recovery seekers came from Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England, the USA and Ukraine.
From January to October 2012, 118,8 thousand Ukrainian tourists came to the praised country, which represents an increase of 51% compared to the 2010 comparison period, prior to the withdrawal of visa obligations on 9 February 2011.
"The Great and Powerful" leads to Moscow: Migrants save money for language
While Members and Citizens' Rights are discussing the benefits of the Law on mandatory language tests for migrants, criminals are already acting with fake certificates
Every year, 13 million guest workers come to Moscow, Saint Petersburg and other cities of Russia.
Most of them are the citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money for the maintenance of families living in the home country.
On 1 December, a law entered into force requiring every worker to pass a test certifying knowledge of Russian language.
So far, this scheme applies only to migrants who want to work in the services sector, in the municipal housing sector and in retail.
However, the tests, according to the Federal Migration Authority, will become mandatory for all guest workers in the future.
Not only do you have to pass language tests, but also tests in Russian history and the basics of legislation.
Language skills must be demonstrated for both the preservation and extension of the work permit.
Exceptions apply only to citizens of countries in which Russian is official language.
Apart from this law, persons who received their certificates of training and diplomas before the collapse of the USSR in 1991 are also excluded.
Purpose, problem and protection of rights
The audit offices will be under the aegide of the Puschkin Institute for Russian Language, the Russian University of People's Friendhood, the Moscow State University, the St Petersburg State University and other Russian universities.
The migrants can pass the tests in all cities; more than 160 corresponding centres have already been opened in Russia.
The initiative to introduce the tests was supported by the members of the State Duma and the Federal Migration Authority.
On the other hand, before the law entered into force in the press, civil rights activists repeatedly asked the following question: What is the result?
What changes does the requirement to show language skills for both the Russians and the guest workers?
Above all, the migration authority's spokesperson is concerned with reducing the number of forced workers.
"Many are now talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers," says Viktor Sebelew, Head of the Federal Migration Authority's Office in Tajikistan.
However, their rights must be protected before they leave.
Only an organized recruitment will solve the problems of foreign workers by 90%.
Migrants face problems without a job, education, language skills and medical examination.
Sebelew is convinced that a future migrants without language skills will inevitably encounter people with evil intentions who put him under the pretext of help into a dark, narrow barracks, where he will endure with dozens of his similar months without food and documents and create 12 to 14 hours a day.
We have many complaints from our migrants.
"In the home you will be promised the One, and upon arrival you will be deceived, their passports will be taken away and not received the promised wage," confirms the head of the main administration for labour migration of the Tajik Migration Authority, Tolib Schwaripov.
Don't yell, boss!
Nevertheless, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who want to earn their money in Russia admit that they cannot control the language of the target country, but can hardly express themselves in writing in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault, rather the evil: only few Turkmen, Usbeken and Tajiken can also afford reasonable primary education.
For in their families there is not even money to feed the children, let alone to buy them decent clothing, shoes and school goods.
As a teenager, these children immediately take the first opportunity to earn money.
"It is difficult without language skills," they admit.
"You feel humiliated and inferior."
Civil rights activists stress the following important aspect of the law.
Only migrants with legal status must pass the test.
If you do not have this status, there is no test and therefore no official work.
Meanwhile, most of the host workers remain illegally in Russia.
"Welcome welcome" or "allowed access"
Many migrants confirm that it is not easy to obtain official status in Russia.
The reason are bureaucratic obstacles and, of course, the linguistic difficulties.
In addition, the legalization costs money: 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
A fake registration can be made quickly and for only one and a half thousand.
The staff of the Russian police know that our documents are largely falsified and we are not registered, and from this they are caused by extortion.
"They want one or two hundred rubles for cigarettes and tea," the Tajike Umed Huschkadamov says to journalists.
"No cost to hide false papers"
Already on the day the law came into force, it turned out that not only the registration documents of migrants can be falsified.
Some fake certificates certifying the completion of the language test have already been seized by Federal Migration Authority employees.
The fake papers were printed with an ordinary colour printer.
Of course, the new owners did not get these for nothing: Every migrants who hoped to be able to save the tests paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is more than twice as much as the cost of the official test: it costs a migrant three thousand rubles.
On the fact that the most important direct task is to protect the system from corruption so that the certificates cannot be easily purchased, both officials and citizens agree.
For the moment, the authorities can only promise guest workers who fall through the test for the first time to receive time for a language course.
In addition, new arrivals without language skills are offered places in areas where there is no need for active understanding with people.
