Poland and space.
Last week, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this space authority at a ministerial meeting of the member countries of the European Space Agency (ESA). As a result, Poland is the second member country of the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became ESA member on 12 November 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and participated in several ESA projects in the following years.
The path of Poland into space, of course, began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, Polish cosmos enthusiasts were dealing with space, not always understanding it.
I remember here, for example, the presentation by A. Šternfeld of December 6, 1933 in the Warsaw Observatory, where the author presented thoughts from his pioneering work "Entry to Cosmonautics".
However, the ideas of the young engineer (b. 1905) made the audience cold, and after years Šternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Gadomski had shown interest in his work.
Šternfeld won the Prix REP-Hirsch, which was founded by Robert Esnault-Peltery and André Louis Hirsch in 1934 for "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became an important champion of astronomy and space.
In Polish magazines he published hundreds of articles and wrote several books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski's worldwide recognized contribution to space development was appreciated by one of the craters named after him on the moon's elongated side.
Already in 1925, a railway Draisine was built in Poland, for which a rocket drive was planned.
Unfortunately, the author of the draft and the details of this project remained unknown.
It is not even clear whether the rocket should be used for starting or braking the draisine.
The information for this purpose is exclusively from the contemporary press.
In 1933, the Polish infantry began to deal with rocket-powered arteries.
The research carried out by the Institute Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in cooperation with Prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Prof. Gustaw Mokrzyckiegi.
The documents submitted show that research had been carried out to the stage of practical tests.
The research was, of course, interrupted by the invasion of the German Wehrmacht.
In 1937, a photoelectric hunting rocket appeared in the specialist press of the draft of a photoelectric hunting rocket by Ing. Rohoziński, and the following year the work "Rakieta - torpeda powitrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by author Leliwa-Krzywoblocky appeared.
Both projects dealt with the military use of rocket drive.
Shortly before the war, all projects for the military use of rocket technology were coordinated by the Previous Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukovy).
The Committee was set up in 1937, but after two years of work it was completed from the beginning of the war.
Further articles on space after the war were published in the Polish press, thanks to the work of the Polish Space Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of this company was made in 1954 in the November issue of Problemy magazine, which dedicated four extensive articles of space.
The article by Prof. M. Subotowicz contains the proposal to establish a space society.
At the time there were already the first projects on satellite technology, and it was to be seen that the exploration of space would have the future.
As early as 1956, the Polish space company PTA tried to join the International Space Federation, founded in 1951, and in fact, PTA became a regular member already in autumn 1956.
The following year, the first PTA chairman, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), was appointed Deputy Chairman of the International Federation for Space.
He had this office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956 the PTA has been significantly involved in the development of the extremely successful meteorological rocket (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), the first Polish rocket for scientific research.
The first type, the RM-1, was completed in 1957, the first one took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a maximum flight height of 1800 m was about 80 cm long and did not weigh 5 kg.
Later an improved version, the RM-1A, was built, and 1959 started flight tests with the two-step missile RM-2 in the Bł the Dów desert.
The rocket was 1.4 m long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
A further stage of development should already be able to do real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should reach an altitude of up to 14.5 km and be used to observe altitude winds.
In 1962, however, further development was discontinued.
The first rockets of the RM type were the Meteor-1 rockets developed from 1962 to 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm and the start weight was 32,5 kg.
Three types were developed from these rockets (Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed from each other in the size of the transport space for scientific instruments.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a transport space with 0.4 litres of capacity, a meteor-1B of 0.34 litres and a meteor-1C of 0.62 litres.
The maximum flight altitude was 37 km for all three types.
From 1965 to 1968, the Meteor 2 rocket was developed in the aviation institute, whose first flight tests began in October 1970.
Meteor-2 had a starting weight of 380 kg and was able to transport a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
After that, the versions Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 were built.
The accession of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) was also worth mentioning in 1960, on which two years later a national COSPAR committee was set up.
Poland also participated in space research with Soviet satellites as part of the Intercosmos programme, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became second Interkosmonaut after the Czech Vladimír Remek.
