Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, expert in US-European relations, Berlin thus balances on a narrow diplomatic level.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had initially signaled that it would vote against the request for an observer status of the Palestinians to the United Nations.
But then Berlin contained itself.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis did in Gaza.
Now, however, because of his special relationship with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time I think it doesn't support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it was about setting up a flight ban zone.
It was finally enforced by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to have a clear position on important international issues?
Yeah, that's right.
This is because it is precisely changing its foreign policy, away from a policy managed by the United States, to a German foreign policy.
It is difficult to say that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans thus find themselves between the fronts.
They are expected to play an independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still touching their role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, as they have France or the UK.
What does a "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It shows the willingness to refer to positions which are independent of those of the USA or European partners in the case of national interests.
I believe that German foreign policy is motivated by economic policy, i.e. from exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are to a certain extent different from those of the other major powers and therefore Germany needs to protect its interests.
Have these economic interests affected the attitude of the Middle East conflict and the vote in the UN?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf states.
Therefore, it must be careful not to push the public, but also the elites, into the Arab countries.
It certainly plays a role.
But I wouldn't want to give it too much weight either, that's not a totally one-sided relationship.
But it certainly plays an important role in German considerations.
Did Germany damage its relations with the USA by abstaining from important decisions, such as voting on Palestine?
I believe that there is great understanding of the German position in Europe and even in the USA.
That's why I don't think this was such a dramatic break as in the Libyan question.
Perhaps it will even show some respect for Germany.
Because it signals that it is taken seriously as an international player and its interests must be considered.
There are various opinions in Europe on the Palestinian initiative.
The U.S., on the other hand, clearly voted for a veto.
Are there differences between the US and many European nations?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I think that the Obama government is secretly very much aware of the European position.
But because of the political situation here, the government cannot, of course, represent this position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always appear.
If you look at the relationships between Obama and Prime Minister Netanjahu, Obama is not so excited about Netanjahus politics.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the US on the one hand, and the position of the main partners in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
It would, of course, be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, which is not at present the case.
So they cannot be part of a wider line and instead have to push things forward from their own position.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in pushing Europe to a European position.
Of course, this is not easy for Germany, because of the relationship with Israel.
It's always been a sensitive topic.
But I think the Germans are clear that they have to play a more independent role.
Does Germany itself see itself as an important international player - does Germany even want to play a leading role?
Or does Germany still find the leading role difficult?
Germany is not yet used to it, that is still unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult for the country to play a greater role.
For example, when we look at the euro crisis, every time Germany takes on a greater role, various anti-German feelings are released.
That doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
This is actually the old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
This is how Germany is in a much more difficult position than the USA.
It must be responsive to different neighbours and opinions, and that is not easy.
Now the US's influence in European policy is constantly decreasing, but the EU is not filling this vacuum at the moment, who else remains there?
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if they don't like it, it's unpleasant to them and it's much more unlovable - c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America are working together to explore the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialises in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
