Conclusion of the Unasur Summit without publication of the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Presidents of the Union of South America (Unasur) ended today in Peru without publication of the Declaration of Lima, which was previously announced and should theoretically be signed by the seven rulers present.
Efe repeatedly tried to gain access to the signed document at the VI. Ordinary meeting of the heads of state and government of the Unasur. Sources in the State and President's Office initially announced that they would hand it over after the clause, however, explained that it would be published at some time on the Peruvian government website.
In the case of questions on the text, they indicated that the content was presented to the press by the President of Peru, Ollanta Humala.
Journalists' access to information about the summit was limited at any time.
During the day, only the image of the presidential meeting without sound was transmitted in the press room with the announcement "Private Session, Limited Audio".
The few information circulated among journalists were received by the press speakers from some of the governments of Unasur present at the meeting, but not from the Peruvian press speaker.
The only document that was distributed during the day was the list of the participating presidents, which caused the hundreds of journalists of various national and international media who demanded more information.
After that, the Bureau of Peru sent the media an e-mail with the "Decision" of the summit, but it was the Declaration of Humala and not the official document for the conclusion of the summit.
Last October, Peru was host to the Third Summit of South America - Arab States (ASPA), and even on this occasion, despite strong invitation from the press, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had previously been announced, was equally not published.
On the official ASPA website you can convince yourself that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities stressed that information systems for journalists would be available, but limited access to information to a large extent.
The summit also ended with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to adopt a judgment of the Hague Court of Justice, which is in line with a border conflict between both countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met during the regional meeting and confirmed that they would accept the decision of the IGH, which begins on Monday in The Hague, in the process that led Lima against Santiago to listen to the pleaters on both sides.
"We will follow and execute the judgment on the differences we are currently presenting to this international court," said Humala along with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and remains a country which adheres to international laws, seeks peaceful solutions to disputes, concludes agreements and submits itself to international courts," Piñera adds, greeting Humala with a handshake in front of the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they would submit to the IGH was made after Colombia had made a decision on the maritime borders with Nicaragua, which considered it a serious mistake to file a complaint against the Bogotá agreement, in which it agreed to submit to the judgments of this international court.
The summit was attended by the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, which has been excluded from Unasur since 2011 after its President Fernando Lugo has been disfellowshipping, did not take part in the meeting.
The guest president Ollanta Humala opened the talks on the morning and ended the summit shortly after lunch in Lima.
The Head of State left the final document, in which it stated that 16 decisions were taken and the lines of action were set for 31 projects between the South American countries over an investment amount of 17 billion dollars.
Regarding the decisions taken, he said that the countries of the Unasur "will take significant steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship, to which we extend the decisions on residence rights."
He announced that measures would be taken to "improve cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and organised cross-border crime, as well as measures to improve access to drugs and the Internet at low prices in all areas of South America and to act jointly and efficiently in the case of natural disasters".
With the crisis in Europe, "economic consolidation (in Latin America) must not take on triumphant challenges, but rather serve to expand our production performance and show our people a better future," said Humala.
"We have decided to give priority to a number of 31 emblematic projects aimed at improving spatial links in South America and especially in rural and border areas... and thus unite our countries and establish new economic forms," said the Peruvian President in a literate statement.
Among these projects would also be five Peruvians lying on the querachsens of his territory from the coast to Brazil, and two of which should ensure a better connection with Ecuador, although he did not give any further details.
The final document also referred to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve for its resumption in the Union of South American nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to continue to remain an integrated region for prosperity and peace and with good neighbourhood relations was another aspect that was highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the president of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before his participation in the regional meeting that on Saturday in Mexico he expected a meeting with his counterpart to Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, to treat the maritime conflict with respect for a judgment of the IGH in question by Bogotá.
"I may meet President Daniel Ortega on the morning (Saturday)," said Santos.
"We will review all these ways - they are not exclusive, and also the agreement with Nicaragua makes discussions with Nicaragua necessary," he underlined.
"I hope to be able to tell the President Ortega that we will treat this matter as civilized and respectfully as possible," added Santos.
Santos and Ortega would meet in Mexico on Saturday, where they intend to be present at the takeover of the new president of this country, Enrique Peña Nito.
